However, these are on different scales, so that is better, that is worse; however, that’s more fluid in my head than these, so these are very separate.

TimeInterview: That one I just went for it. I was visualising a clock in a sense, and I was just thinking to me, okay… What times to me are the earliest? What do I class as being the latest times? And I just placed it as if there was a clock of some sort, so that’s the reason behind that one.
QuantityInterview: Once again, it’s ordering, so I don’t know why I did it this way instead of going the other way, but yeah – just putting them into order, again starting with the best, right the way down to the least this time, so… I don’t know why. It’s just ordering. I don’t know whether it’s because I’m an organised person, so I tend to write things in particular orders.
ValenceInterview: This one just going from worst to best, starting low, going high, reaching for that end goal. I don’t know [why it’s going horizontally rather than vertically]… whether it’s because when we write obviously we go from right to left… So left to right, sorry, yeah, rather than doing it in lines. I don’t know but yeah, that was that one. I think more of this timeline again going on, so. I think being a history teacher as well, we tend to work a lot with timelines, so there you go.

TimeInterview: So the earliest again is at the bottom, and then later, again, has nothing specific, but latest does, so I’ve gone there at the top with that but it’s kind of in line, but that’s like an offset of that, and then earliest just below latest.
QuantityInterview: I put most near the top, obviously, and then just below it I put less, and least is the lowest one of all, so I put that right down the bottom and then more… Every one, I’ve put one to the side so it’s not in line with it, so I’ve gone just off it with more. So you’ve got most but then you can have more, but you can’t really put a numerical value on it, so I’ve just gone… So that could be most but then you could add more to most, couldn’t you? In a weird way. Least is at the bottom. I definitely thought I was gonna put that right at the bottom because there’s not like ‘leaster’ as a word. But it’s all in line, but that’s like an off one, so that’s how I’ve kind of gone with that.
ValenceInterview: Same again, worst at the bottom, best at the top. Worse just below it and better’s like an offcut of best. So every one I do there’s an off one of that… I dunno why.

TimeInterview: Same [as valence]. I kind of did it like order in time, like a timeline, from left to right.
QuantityInterview: And that one, again, I kind of imagined a graph, like least… like a bar chart with most at the top.
ValenceInterview: I just felt like I should kind of put them in order each time, so I felt like better… In fact, I’ve done it the wrong way round to what I should have done, but I felt like these two should be higher up on the page, and these two should be further down.

TimeInterview: Because it was to do with time, I sort of envisaged a bit of a timeline, and then I just did it chronologically across the centre of the page, because I felt like that was the most visually pleasing, but then I realised I haven’t spaced them as evenly as I perhaps would have liked. But yeah, just chronological order from left to right
QuantityInterview: This was me sort of thinking, you know, things that are the best or the most important, you’d normally put on top, and the least important would be at the bottom. And I went in order from least to most, but this time vertically, again through the middle of the page, just for evenness.
ValenceInterview: Similar rationale to the second [quantity] one – best being on top, the worst being at the bottom, and going up again through the centre of the page as a result.

TimeInterview: So all of them seem like, I dunno, like I’ve tried to put them into some sort of sequence. So this one seemed more chronological, because it was a time-based one, so the latest one I’ve put on the very right hand side of the paper, so it makes a kind of timeline. Perhaps that’s the historian in me speaking, I don’t know.
QuantityInterview: This one reminded me of when you get those questionnaires, but again it just seemed like it kind of fitted into a timeline-based thing, with less and more… It’s not chronological, but it’s still categorised along a line, kind of thing. And I imagine you might see where you are along these points.
ValenceInterview: And then, finally, again, quite similar [to quantity]. Categorising them across, again, an imaginary horizontal line from worst to best. I tried to make it equal.

TimeInterview: Again, the most positive word at the top, ‘cause I’m always early everywhere. Superlatives top and bottom, so the same logic as behind the last one [valence].
QuantityInterview: Same as the first two [time and valence] really. ‘Cause that’s the best of the most of something… Actually, thinking about it, maybe not. And then the superlatives top and bottom.
ValenceInterview: Okay, so I went from the most positive superlative at the top, followed by a comparative, and then progressing down to the most negative superlative. [I put best at the top and worst at the bottom] because the positive goes at the top – I don’t know, it just goes at the top. It’s where it lives. That’s its eyes.

TimeInterview: Like before I put earliest at the very very left-hand side, sort of in the middle of the page, because to me that’s as early as you can get. Then earlier I considered it to be earlier than the expected time, so earlier than the time of arrival, so you’re the earliest person, then you’re earlier, and then later comes after the expected time, and then latest as far away from earliest as possible.
QuantityInterview: I put least very far down on the left-hand side because for me that’s the superlative form of the word, so it’s right at the bottom. I put less past the left-hand side of the half of the page, because less is less than the expected amount, and I put more progressively past that, past the halfway point, and I put most almost as far as least was, on the right-hand side, so they’re at polar opposites to one another.
ValenceInterview: And very similar [to time] with the other one too. Worst I pushed right over to left-hand side. I put worse quite closer to worst, actually, because I think worst is significantly lower down the scale than the expected standard for me. I’m a bit of a perfectionist when it comes to that sort of thing, so for me worse is bad and worst is really really bad. Better, for me, I put that relatively close to the middle of the page, because as far as I’m concerned, being better than what I would consider to be the expected standard is fine, but you wanna be the best, and for me I conceive best to be quite far ahead of better, because I think it’s much much more difficult to be the best at something, and I think the difference between people who are better at something and are best at something in my experience are significantly better, proportionally, than people who are worst at something are. So there’s a big difference between better and best, and there’s less of a difference between worse and worst. I thought of it as a scale, a left-to-right scale, you know because that’s how we read – from left to right, that’s how I conceive things to be on a continuum scale, so I put them all horizontally for that reason. I’m not a big believer in rank and hierarchy. I’m a believer in performance across the way, so there we go.

TimeInterview: So earlier and then later, and I put earliest and then latest. So two end points and then earlier, but then latest. [This one’s different to quantity] I suppose because it’s time, so [with quantity] I was thinking more about objects, whereas this one’s looking at, I suppose, a timeline.
QuantityInterview: So I kind of went from more and then least, and then more but less, so I kind of went with a little pattern. So more at the top and then least and then, and that's more than least, and then less. So [more up is more], I suppose because if you pour a glass of pop or something, more is more as you go up.
ValenceInterview: So best and then worst, and then I went worse then better, and then better. I suppose [this one’s vertical] because if you’re better, then you’re at the top, and then worst is at the bottom – that’s probably what my mind was thinking.

TimeInterview: Same principle [as for quantity] really. If you’re early, you’re the earliest, you’re on time, in my mind. And if you’re late or late, it’s not a good thing, so it’s considered a lower issue, really.
QuantityInterview: I was thinking that’s the most you could have of something. You could want more of something, but most is the ultimate. I guess it’s a hierarchical thing. Top of the pile – most. Bottom of the pile – least.
ValenceInterview: I guess it’s the same principles [as time and quantity] really. Ah, I meant to put that the other way around. Why have I done that? It should have been the other way around. And for the same reason – the best is at the top, and then worst is at the bottom. You can get better, but best is your best, and better’s on route to being best.
